#include<stdio.h>
#include<string.h>
void fun(char **);
int main()
{
        char *argv[]={"ab","cd","ef","gh"};
        fun(argv);
        return 0;
}
void fun(char **p)
{
        char *t;
        t=(p+=sizeof(int))[-1];
        printf("%s\n",t);
}
///////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
1️⃣ Initial Memory

In main:

char *argv[]={"ab","cd","ef","gh"};

Memory:

argv[0] → "ab"
argv[1] → "cd"
argv[2] → "ef"
argv[3] → "gh"

When calling:

fun(argv)

p receives address of argv[0].

p → argv[0]
2️⃣ Expression inside fun
t = (p += sizeof(int))[-1];

Break it step by step.

Step A — p += sizeof(int)

Assume a 32-bit system:

sizeof(int) = 4

But p is char **, so pointer arithmetic moves 4 elements, not 4 bytes.

p = p + 4

So pointer becomes:
p → argv[4]

But array only has elements up to argv[3].

So now:

p → one element beyond the array
Step B — [-1]

Expression:

(p += sizeof(int))[-1]

means:

*(p - 1)

Since:

p → argv[4]

then:

p[-1] → argv[3]
3️⃣ Value stored in t
t = argv[3]
argv[3] → "gh"

So:

t → "gh"
4️⃣ printf
printf("%s\n",t);

prints:

gh
5️⃣ Final Output
gh
6️⃣ Important Interview Concepts
Pointer arithmetic rule
p + n  → moves n elements

not n bytes.

Negative indexing
p[-1] == *(p-1)
7️⃣ Why sizeof(int) is confusing here

Using

p += sizeof(int)

is dangerous because it depends on system size.

Better version would be:

p += 4;
8️⃣ Safe mental model
p → argv[0]
p += 4 → argv[4]
p[-1] → argv[3]

